rintendent Steve </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Ottaway</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, following complaints from some local residents, and previous articles and letters in the local newspaper, the Herts Advertiser, regarding Helicopter overflying nuisance.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Those present –</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Chie</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">f Superintendent Steve </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Ottaway</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">  –</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Herts Police</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">(`SO’)</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Executive Officer Doug MacKay – Chiltern Air Support unit</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">(`DM’)</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Mr Austin </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Trueman</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> – </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Redbourn</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Resident</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">(`AT’)</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Mr Colin Weaver – Harpenden Resident</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">(`CW’)</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">CW had raised both noise and safety is</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">sues in previous correspondence with SO. CW stated he had many </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">years experience</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> with `hi-tech’ machinery in the North Sea Oil &amp; Gas Industry as a Professional Mechanical Engineer and had seen many oil and gas rig rotating machinery failures over the years.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> He had also flown as a passenger in North Sea helicopters and pointed out that over a hundred men had died in CAA regulated twin </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">engined</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> helicopter crashes in the course of North Sea operations.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Introducing himself, DM explained that as the Helicopter Uni</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">t Executive Officer, he answers to the Chief Constable of Thames Valley, Sara Thornton, and not to Hertfordshire Constabulary. Sara Thornton holds the “operating licence” but Chiltern Air Support Unit (CASU) is managed by a Board of senior managers from al</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">l three Forces and DM is answerable to that Board.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">DM explained that the Chiltern Air Support Unit is subject to CAA regulation (but has some exemptions - </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">eg</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> low flying for Police Operations) and that it operates twin </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">engined</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> craft in order to maximise saf</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ety and that safety is the number one concern of all involved with the Unit. Police helicopter operations are limited to Visual Flight Rules (VFR) and have an absolute minimum cloud ceiling of 300 feet, but 1000 feet is generally used as the `norm’ for mos</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">t operations The Police helicopters operate in accordance with manuals agreed with the CAA in which they have an exemption in respect to the low flying rules but are still bound by the requirement to land clear in case of a total engine(s) failure.  </span><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Not co</span><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">mpletely accurate summary</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">DM explained that the Chiltern Air Support Unit aims to operate at 1,000 to 1,500 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">feet</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> unless weather conditions do not permit or there is an operational necessity to do otherwise. All agreed that helicopters are noisy especially</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> when operated at "low level".</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> However, both AT and CW had personally seen the Police EC135 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Eurocopter</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">(s) operating in `transit mode’ in clear weather conditions at what appeared to be much lower heights than those mentioned by DM. DM, as Unit Executive Of</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ficer, agreed to remind the Pilots of the noise impact of low level `in transit’ operations, and that overflying of villages </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">etc</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> should be avoided where possible. DM would also re-iterate to Pilots that operation at 1000 to 1500 feet height should be the `</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">norm’ where weather conditions permit.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">DM, in response to a question from AT, explained that the Police helicopter unit is shared between Hertfordshire, Bedfordshire and Thames Valley at the total cost of approximately £2 million excluding `normal’ Police </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">salaries for the Police Officer on </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">heli</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, and Police Management /Admin staff.  The cost is split on a population basis and, as a result, Hertfordshire pays approximately 25% (i.e. £500,000). There are in fact 2 Helicopters, one based at RAF Benson, and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">the other at RAF </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Henlow</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">DM advised that approximately 1100 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">hours worth</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> of sorties per aircraft are flown each year. AT and CW pointed out the negative impact that noise from Police helicopters operations is having on the local community and therefore the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">general reputation of the Police within that community. Both pointed out that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Redbourn</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and Harpenden residents were generally likely to be supportive of the Police Force, and that it would be regrettable if over reliance on Helicopter operations was leadin</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">g to alienation.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">CW asked about the operations the Police </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Heli</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> was used for. SO stated that less than 1% of the Police helicopter time is used in respect to road traffic issues. CW stated that he was not happy with the use of the helicopter for more minor </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">policing – such as the use of two Helicopters to chase four individuals allegedly involved in hare coursing, or shoplifting. AT also commented that the over use of Helicopters could lead to criticism that the UK was becoming a `Big Brother’ surveillance so</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ciety. DM and SO explained that the Helicopter was also involved in 'finding' elderly people with Alzheimer’s disease </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">etc</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> as well as chasing stolen cars. SO stated that cars were now so secure that thieves were now entering houses and threatening individua</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ls to obtain car keys. Police helicopters have also been used to transit injured and/or sick people when the use of an air ambulance is not available and/or when the Police helicopter was in the closest proximity. This occurred on 38 occasions last year.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">D</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">M was explained that Harpenden and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Redbourn</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> are part of the airspace controlled by Luton Airport and air traffic control will sometimes give instructions in respect of flying height to be used when transiting or operating in that airspace.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> AT stated that h</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">e had received contradictory comments from Luton Airport Air Traffic control on this topic.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">All agreed that the operational necessity is an area is driven by national and local priorities and that we may never reach agreement that those priorities are righ</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">t nor that we will be able to influence them.  The use of the helicopter is an operational decision governed by the CASU management board - not the Police Authority. In essence the helicopter is a tool to support delivery of policing priorities (which are </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">set by Police Authorities) and the management board will determine its deployment criteria, operating hours </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">etc</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and then operational managers use the helicopter within those guidelines.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">SO offered to arrange a follow-up meeting for October/November this ye</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ar.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">July/August 2008</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Meeting note Revision Status</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">1</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">st</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Draft – Steve </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Ottaway</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, 10 July, 2008</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">2</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">nd</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Draft incorporating comments from Austin </span><span style="font-family:'Times